How can I get the current sceneData that can be passed as an argument in excalidrawAPI.updateScene(sceneData);

**Context:** I'm building my own collaboration feature and just want to cache and send/update the current scene data myself. So far I only see way to update it and no way to get the current scene data.

cc: @ad1992

So `initialData.files` actually seems to be working fine for me. It's the `getFiles` that wasn't working as expected.

My workaround was to move saving the scene state to storage out of that `useEffect` and into a debounced function in `onChange` instead, like this:

```js
<Excalidraw
  ref={callbackRef}
  initialData={createInitialData()}
  UIOptions={{ canvasActions: { export: false, loadScene: false } }}
  onChange={debounce((elements, state, files) => {
    sessionStorage.setItem(
      "excalidrawState",
      serializeAsJSON(elements, state, files, "local")
    );
    console.debug("saved sketchpad state to storage");
  }, 500)}
/>
```

Then when the widget re-opens, I initialize the scene with `initialData` like this:

```js
function createInitialData() {
  let initialData: IExcalidrawInitialData = {};

  initialData.scrollToContent = true;

  const ss = sessionStorage.getItem("excalidrawState");

  if (ss) {
    const excalidrawState = JSON.parse(ss);
    initialData.appState = excalidrawState.appState;
    initialData.elements = excalidrawState.elements;
    initialData.files = excalidrawState.files;
  } else {
    initialData.appState = {
      viewBackgroundColor: "#edf2ff",
      currentItemStrokeColor: "#c92a2a",
      currentItemStrokeWidth: 4,
      currentItemFontSize: 36,
    };
  }

  return initialData;
}
```

Unfortunately we cannot do that. In some places in our code we use this variable to enable debugging features.

For now I found a workaround by directly using `@excalidraw/excalidraw/dist/excalidraw.production.min` instead of `@excalidraw/excalidraw`
And applying the types by creating a `d.ts` file with 
```
declare module '@excalidraw/excalidraw/dist/excalidraw.production.min' {
  import Excalidraw from '@excalidraw/excalidraw/types';
  export default Excalidraw;
}
```

Thanks for the help anyway. Cheers!

Created this violentmonkey script with AI. Sets right click to pan, scroll wheel to zoom. Works well for me in brave. Right click menu in excalidraw is not really useful so I don't lose anything.

```js
// ==UserScript==
// @name         Excalidraw: Wheel-Zoom + Right-Click Pan
// @namespace    excalidraw-wheel-zoom-rmb-pan
// @version      1.0
// @description  Scroll wheel zooms (centered on cursor). Right-click + drag pans. Native context menu suppressed.
// @match        https://excalidraw.com/*
// @grant        none
// @run-at       document-idle
// ==/UserScript==

(function () {
  'use strict';

  const mkOpts = (e, extra) => Object.assign({
    bubbles: true, cancelable: true, composed: true, view: window,
    clientX: e.clientX, clientY: e.clientY,
    screenX: e.screenX, screenY: e.screenY,
    ctrlKey: e.ctrlKey, shiftKey: e.shiftKey, altKey: e.altKey, metaKey: e.metaKey,
  }, extra);

  const firePointer = (type, target, e, extra) =>
    target.dispatchEvent(new PointerEvent(type, mkOpts(e, Object.assign({
      pointerId: e.pointerId ?? 1, pointerType: 'mouse', isPrimary: true,
    }, extra))));

  const fireMouse = (type, target, e, extra) =>
    target.dispatchEvent(new MouseEvent(type, mkOpts(e, extra)));

  // ---------- 1. Wheel -> Zoom (centered on cursor) ----------
  window.addEventListener('wheel', (e) => {
    if (!e.isTrusted || e.ctrlKey || e.metaKey) return; // ignore synthetic + already-zoom events
    e.preventDefault();
    e.stopImmediatePropagation();

    e.target.dispatchEvent(new WheelEvent('wheel', mkOpts(e, {
      deltaX: 0, deltaY: e.deltaY, deltaZ: e.deltaZ, deltaMode: e.deltaMode,
      ctrlKey: true, // <- Excalidraw's native zoom trigger
    })));
  }, { capture: true, passive: false });

  // ---------- 2. Right-click + drag -> Pan ----------
  let panning = false;
  let panTarget = null;

  window.addEventListener('contextmenu', (e) => {
    if (!e.isTrusted) return;
    e.preventDefault();
    e.stopImmediatePropagation();
  }, { capture: true });

  window.addEventListener('pointerdown', (e) => {
    if (!e.isTrusted || e.button !== 2) return;
    e.preventDefault();
    e.stopImmediatePropagation();
    panning = true;
    panTarget = e.target;
    firePointer('pointerdown', panTarget, e, { button: 1, buttons: 4 });
    fireMouse('mousedown', panTarget, e, { button: 1, buttons: 4 });
  }, { capture: true });

  window.addEventListener('pointermove', (e) => {
    if (!e.isTrusted || !panning) return;
    if (!(e.buttons & 2)) { endPan(e); return; } // safety: right button released elsewhere
    e.preventDefault();
    e.stopImmediatePropagation();
    firePointer('pointermove', panTarget, e, { button: -1, buttons: 4 });
    fireMouse('mousemove', panTarget, e, { button: -1, buttons: 4 });
  }, { capture: true });

  function endPan(e) {
    if (!panning) return;
    panning = false;
    e.preventDefault();
    e.stopImmediatePropagation();
    firePointer('pointerup', panTarget, e, { button: 1, buttons: 0 });
    fireMouse('mouseup', panTarget, e, { button: 1, buttons: 0 });
    panTarget = null;
  }

  window.addEventListener('pointerup', (e) => {
    if (!e.isTrusted || e.button !== 2) return;
    endPan(e);
  }, { capture: true });

  window.addEventListener('blur', () => { panning = false; panTarget = null; });
})();
```

